0–1361":"1300–1361","1300–1359":"1300–1359","1326–Female":"1326–Overleden","1273–Male":"1273–Overleden","1275–Female":"1275–Overleden","1326":"1326","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1275":"1275","1361":"1361","1273":"1273","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Smisby, Derbyshire, England":"Smisby, Derbyshire, England","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England"},"en":{"1300–1361":"1300–1361","1300–1359":"1300–1359","1326–Female":"1326–Deceased","1273–Male":"1273–Deceased","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1326":"1326","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1275":"1275","1361":"1361","1273":"1273","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Smisby, Derbyshire, England":"Smisby, Derbyshire, England","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Sale (Cheshire), or from any of several minor places or topographic features named from Middle English <i>sale</i>, <i>salle</i> ‘sallow, willow’ (Old English <i>s(e)alh</i>). See also   Seal  , with which this name may often have interchanged.","English: from Middle English <i>sal(e)</i> ‘hall’ (Old English <i>sæl</i>, Old French <i>sale</i>, Old Norse <i>salr</i>), translated by medieval clerks as Latin <i>aula</i>. The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived or worked in a hall, or occupational, for someone who worked at a hall as a servant. This was the name of an Anglo-Norman family who had settled in County Tipperary, Ireland, by the 13th century. The name was Gaelicized as <b>de Sál</b>, hence the Anglicized form   Saul   which has been widely adopted in Ireland.","Croatian (<b>Šale</b>): probably from a pet form of the personal name <i>Šanto</i>, a Croatized form of Italian   Santo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sallows","meanings":["English (Essex and Suffolk): topographic name from Middle English <i>salwe</i> ‘sallow (a species of willow)’ (Old English <i>s(e)alh</i>), with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. Compare   Sale  ."]},{"name":"Sales","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Efren, Alberto, Francisco, Manuel, Camilo, Carlos, Fernando, Juan, Juanita, Mario, Ofelia.","English: variant of   Sale   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. The Middle English plural form was probably often in variation with the singular form. The surname is uncommon in southwestern England but may derive there from Zeals (Wiltshire), and also from the plural form of Old English <i>sealh</i> ‘willow’; see   Seal  .","Catalan, Spanish, and French (Occitan): habitational name from any of the places called Sales, like Sales de Llierca (Catalonia), from the plural of   Sala   1. Compare   De Sales  ."]},{"name":"Salis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Ruben, Amparo, Armando, Emilio, Juana, Rodolfo.","Italian (Sardinia): plural form of   Sale   ‘salt’.","French: variant of <b>Salies</b>, a habitational name from a placename Salies in Haute-Garonne and Pyrénées-Atlantiques, ultimately derived from Latin <i>salina</i> ‘salt marsh, salt pan, saltworks’."]},{"name":"Seal","meanings":["English: either a habitational name from Seal (Kent), Seale (Surrey), or Sele in Upper Beeding (Sussex), all of which probably derive from Old English <i>sele</i> ‘hall, building’ (though the Surrey placename may arise from Old English <i>sēale</i>, dative form of <i>salh</i> ‘willow’), or else a topographic name for someone who lived at a boggy patch (Kentish Middle English and Old English <i>sele</i>) or a hall. Compare   Sale   1-2.","English: habitational name from Overseal or Netherseal (Derbyshire), probably from Old English <i>scegel</i> ‘small wood’.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by a willow copse or at a place marked by a willow or willows, from Middle English <i>sele</i> ‘willow’ (Old English <i>sele</i>), in northern England representing Old Norse <i>selja</i> and in southwestern England representing Old English (West Saxon) <i>sealh</i>. The name was probably interchangeable with the synonymous Middle English <i>sale</i> (Old English <i>salh</i>, Old Norse <i>salr</i>), and in some cases the surname may have functioned as a variant of   Sale  . In southwestern England initial <i>S-</i> was frequently voiced to <i>Z-</i>, as in the Wiltshire placename Zeals (from the plural form of Old English <i>sealh</i>). However, the medieval form of the placename is overwhelmingly in the plural, and this may also survive as   Sales  ."]},{"name":"Saile","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Elke, Kurt, Volker.","English: variant of   Sale  .","German: older form of   Seiler  ."]},{"name":"Sayle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik.","Manx (Isle of Man): variant of   Sale   1.","Possibly a variant or an Americanized form of German   Saile  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Sale was born in 1300, in Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, his father, John Sale, was 27 and his mother, Mrs. John Sale Sr., was 25. He married Ann Holmes in Smisby, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1361, in his hometown, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1300–1361":"1300–1361","1300–1359":"1300–1359","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","1273–Male":"1273–Surnud","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1326":"1326","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1275":"1275","1361":"1361","1273":"1273","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Smisby, Derbyshire, England":"Smisby, Derbyshire, England","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1300–1361":"1300–1361","1300–1359":"1300–1359","1326–Female":"1326–Kuollut","1273–Male":"1273–Kuollut","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1326":"1326","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1275":"1275","1361":"1361","1273":"1273","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire